# Integration Guide: BridgeVehicleHardware + VehicleDaemon

Generated by `vhal-gen`. This guide works with **any Android 14 VHAL tag** from Gerrit.

## Architecture

```
Vehicle Network (UDP)
        |
┌──────────────────────────────────────────┐
│  Vehicle Body SDK (sdk/ directory)       │
│  com/     -> ComConfig, CanConfig,       │
│              com_utils (pack/unpack)     │
│  can_io/  -> iodata (wire format)        │
│  app/swc/ -> Read_App_Signal_Data.h/cpp  │  <- get_*() RX getters
│              Write_App_Signal_Data.h/cpp  │  <- set_*() TX setters
└──────────────┬───────────────────────────┘
               |  calls get_*/set_*
┌──────────────────────────────────────────┐
│  VehicleDaemon (child process of VHAL)     │
│  - Spawned via fork()+exec() by Bridge   │
│  - Communicates over socketpair (STDIN)  │
│  - Polls SDK get_*() for RX signals      │
│  - Calls SDK set_*() for TX signals      │
│  - Sends PROPERTY_CHANGED to bridge      │
│  - Handles GET/SET from bridge           │
└──────────────┬───────────────────────────┘
               |  socketpair IPC
┌──────────────────────────────────────────┐
│  BridgeVehicleHardware (generated)       │
│  - IVehicleHardware implementation       │
│  - Spawns daemon as child process        │
│  - Watchdog: auto-respawns on crash      │
│  - Android CarService consumes this      │
└──────────────────────────────────────────┘
```

## What Was Generated

The generator placed bridge files in `impl/bridge/` and applied the following
modifications to the stock VHAL source:

- **VehicleService.cpp** — modified to use BridgeVehicleHardware instead of FakeVehicleHardware
- **vhal/Android.bp** — updated to link BridgeVehicleHardware and libjsoncpp

The daemon is spawned as a child process of the VHAL service. No separate init
service or `.rc` file is needed — all modifications are contained within the
VHAL module.

## Prerequisites

- AOSP source tree synced with an Android 14 automotive target
- The VHAL source at `hardware/interfaces/automotive/vehicle/aidl/`

## Build

```bash
cd $AOSP_ROOT
source build/envsetup.sh
lunch <your-automotive-target>

# Build just the VHAL module (includes bridge + daemon)
cd hardware/interfaces/automotive/vehicle/aidl/impl
mma
```

## Deploy to Emulator

```bash
# Start emulator with writable system
emulator -writable-system &

# Wait for boot, then push
adb root
adb remount
adb push $OUT/vendor/bin/hw/android.hardware.automotive.vehicle@V*-default-service \
         /vendor/bin/hw/
adb push $OUT/vendor/bin/vehicle-daemon /vendor/bin/
adb push $OUT/vendor/etc/automotive/vhal/DefaultProperties.json \
         /vendor/etc/automotive/vhal/

# Set SELinux permissive for initial testing
adb shell setenforce 0

# Restart VHAL (daemon is auto-spawned as a child process)
adb shell stop vehicle_hal_server 2>/dev/null; adb shell stop vendor.vehicle.hal.default
adb shell start vendor.vehicle.hal.default
```

## Verify

```bash
# Check VHAL service is running with bridge
adb logcat -s BridgeVHAL:* VehicleService:*

# Check daemon is running (spawned as child of VHAL)
adb logcat -s VehicleDaemon:*

# Check properties are registered
adb shell dumpsys car_service | grep -i "property count"
```

## Vehicle Body SDK

The `sdk/` directory contains the Vehicle Body SDK files, copied verbatim from
the reference implementation. These files handle:

- **COM layer** (`com/`): Signal bit-packing/unpacking and buffer management
- **CAN I/O** (`can_io/`): Wire format serialization
- **Signal API** (`app/swc/`): High-level `get_*()` / `set_*()` functions

The daemon calls `get_*()` to read RX signal values and `set_*()` to write TX
signal values. The SDK's COM layer manages the underlying UDP transport and
PDU buffers -- the daemon does not need its own transport implementation.

> **Important:** Do NOT modify the SDK files. They are maintained separately
> and should be updated by replacing the entire `sdk/` directory.

